thought.text:
Now let me understand the issue more deeply. The `Cell.GetCellLength(string text)` method iterates through the text character by character:

```csharp
public static int GetCellLength(ReadOnlySpan<char> text)
{
    var sum = 0;
    foreach (var rune in text)
    {
        sum += GetCellLength(rune);
    }
    return sum;
}
```

The problem is: `foreach (var rune in text)` on a `ReadOnlySpan<char>` iterates over `char` values, NOT over Unicode runes. So when an emoji like 💩 is a surrogate pair (2 chars: `\uD83D\uDCA9`), each char of the pair is looked up individually. The first char `\uD83D` (high surrogate) would likely return -1 or 0, and `\uDCA9` (low surrogate) might also return -1 or 0, giving a total width of 0 or incorrect for the emoji.

Wait - actually, let me check this more carefully. Let me also check what `UnicodeCalculator.GetWidth` returns for these characters:

